% KIMI-THEORY-1 Deliverable: Discussion paragraph — Ensemble HAT theoretical grounding
% ~4 sentences, insertion point: Discussion \S6.1 where Ensemble HAT is first discussed

The empirical effectiveness of Ensemble HAT is theoretically grounded in its distribution-matching objective (Eq.~\ref{eq:hat-ensemble-distribution}): a second-order expansion in the D2D mismatch amplitude reveals an implicit Fisher-weighted gradient-squared regularizer that penalizes loss sensitivity to multiplicative weight perturbations (Supplementary Note S-Theory). This pushes the optimizer toward flat minima in the $M$-direction, so that fresh device instances drawn from the same fabrication distribution land near a minimum with high probability. The structural analogy to dropout-as-$L_2$ \citep{wager2013dropout} is a close \emph{structural analogue}, with the physical D2D variance $\sigma_{\text{D2D}}^2$ playing the role of the dropout rate. Consequently, the hardware-instance overfitting gap---the Standard$\to$Ensemble collapse of 76~pp (canonical, zone 3A) and 78~pp (OPECT, zone 3A) reported in Results---is not an artifact of hyperparameter tuning but a direct consequence of training on a single fixed mismatch realization versus matching the full deployment distribution.
